   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition">
                <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                   <lb n="2"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Seia">Seie</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Affias">Affiadi</name>
               </persName>,
                   <lb n="3"/>
               <expan><abbr>co</abbr><ex>n</ex><abbr>iugi</abbr></expan> merenti.
                   <lb n="4"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="praenomen" key="Marcus">
                     <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>arcus</ex></expan>
                  </name>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Caecilius">Caecilius</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Urbanicus">Ur
                   <lb n="5" break="no"/>bicus</name>
               </persName>.
                </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. To Seia Affias, deserving wife. Marcus Caecilius
               Urbicus (made this). </p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>Line 2, "E" for "AE" in "Seie."</p>
            <p>Final “-e” for the dative “Seie” in line 2, usually used for proper names of Greek
               origin, but Schulze attributes an Etruscan origin to the gens Seia (Tuck).</p>
            <p>Line 2: Aeeladi (CIL), Afeladi (Tuck)</p>
         </div>
